ting granulomas are characteristic microscopic findings in inflammatory bowel disease. These structures form when activated macrophages cluster together and some fuse to form giant cells. Unlike tuberculous granulomas, they lack central necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the distribution of non-caseating granulomas in inflammatory bowel disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Present throughout bowel wall in ulcerative colitis only","Present in serosa only in Crohn disease and ulcerative colitis","Present in mucosa only in Crohn disease and ulcerative colitis","Present in submucosa only in Crohn disease","Present throughout bowel wall in Crohn disease only"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-caseating granulomas are a key distinguishing feature between Crohn disease and ulcerative colitis. \u003Cstrong\u003EPresent throughout bowel wall in Crohn disease only\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because these granulomas can occur in any layer of the bowel wall (transmural inflammation) but are only found in Crohn disease, not ulcerative colitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresent throughout bowel wall in ulcerative colitis only\u003C/strong\u003E - Ulcerative colitis inflammation is limited to the mucosa and submucosa, and granulomas are not a feature\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresent in serosa only in Crohn disease and ulcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E - Granulomas are not found in ulcerative colitis, and in Crohn disease they can occur in any layer\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresent in mucosa only in Crohn disease and ulcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E - Granulomas are not a feature of ulcerative colitis and are not limited to the mucosa in Crohn disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresent in submucosa only in Crohn disease\u003C/strong\u003E - Granulomas can occur in any layer of the bowel wall in Crohn disease, not just the submucosa\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Non-caseating granulomas are a hallmark histological finding in Crohn disease but not ulcerative colitis","Non-caseating granulomas can occur in any layer of the bowel wall in Crohn disease (transmural inflammation)","Ulcerative colitis inflammation is limited to the mucosa and submucosa layers"],"references":["Cai Z, Wang S, Li J. Treatment of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Comprehensive Review. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 Dec 20;8:765474. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2021.765474. PMID: 34988090; PMCID: PMC8720971","McDowell C, Farooq U, Haseeb M. Inflammatory Bowel Disease. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262182","Fakhoury M, Negrulj R, Mooranian A, Al-Salami H. Inflammatory bowel disease: clinical aspects and treatments. J Inflamm Res. 2014 Jun 23;7:113-20. doi: 10.2147/JIR.S65979. PMID: 25075198; PMCID: PMC4106026","Tavakoli P, Vollmer-Conna U, Hadzi-Pavlovic D, Grimm MC. A Review of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Model of Microbial, Immune and Neuropsychological Integration. Public Health Rev. 2021 May 5;42:1603990. doi: 10.3389/phrs.2021.1603990. PMID: 34692176; PMCID: PMC8386758","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15412"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54780"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:46:30+10:30",